THE ROLE OF MEMBRANE’S SURFACE PROPERTIES
The surface properties substantially affect the parameters of electroconvection. To gain insight into the nature of this effect, we formulate the following conditions:
—the realization of intense electroconvection requires the presence of electric field with two components: the normal component which creates the extended space charge region and the tangential component which is responsible for the SCR sliding over the surface [63, 64, 108, 109]. Note that even for the homogeneous surface when EC is developed by the mechanism of electrokinetic instability of Rubinstein–Zaltzman [28], the tangential component is present because the current lines bend round the regions of depleted solution at the membrane surface (Fig. 9b);
—the tangential component appears on the boundaries of surface regions with the high and the low conductivity and also at surface ridges and valleys (Fig. 11). Thus, the distance between such boundaries along the membrane surface essentially determines the distance between individual vortices;
—the sliding of EC vortices over the surface becomes easier if the slide surface is relatively hydrophobic;
—insofar as EC vortices tend to acquire the circular form (in their two-dimensional section), then to obtain vortices capable of substantially affecting the mass transfer (i.e., having the size comparable with the diffusion layer thickness δ), the size of heterogeneities on the membrane surface should also be comparable with δ [28, 36, 45, 63, 109, 110].
Below we show which effects can be attained by varying electric heterogeneity, the degree of hydrophobicity, or by forming a relief on the membrane surface.
